<h2 id=3D"hid2" class=3D"subsection">Preliminaries</h2>
<p>
   Let us review some notions that are essential to understand the Gram-Sch=
midt
   process.
</p>
<p>
   Remember that two vectors
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"9" height=3D"24" src=3D"d=
ata:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRA=
EAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$r$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4234px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"9" height=3D"24" src=3D"d=
ata:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRA=
EAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$s$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4210px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   are said to be orthogonal if and only if their
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/inner-product">inner=
 product</a> is equal to zero,
   that
   is,<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"75" height=3D"38=
" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAAB=
AAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq1]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2742p=
x;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   Given an inner product, we can define the
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/vector-norm">norm</a=
> (length) of a vector
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"9" height=3D"24" src=3D"d=
ata:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRA=
EAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$s$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4210px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   as
   follows:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"105" height=
=3D"42" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq2]" style=3D"background-position:0px =
-2127px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   A set of vectors is called orthonormal if and only if its elements have =
unit
   norm and are orthogonal to each other. In other words, a set of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"14" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"K" style=3D"background-position:0px -4137px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   vectors
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"94" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq3]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2409px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   is orthonormal if and only
   if<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"178" height=3D"74=
" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAAB=
AAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq4]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1190p=
x;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   We have proved that the vectors of an orthonormal set are
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/linear-independence"=
>linearly independent</a>.
</p>
<p>
   When a  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/basis-of-a-li=
near-space">basis</a> for a
   vector space is also an orthonormal set, it is called an
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/orthonormal-basis">o=
rthonormal basis</a>.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid3" class=3D"subsection">Projections on orthonormal sets</h2>
<p>
   In the Gram-Schmidt process, we repeatedly use the next proposition, whi=
ch
   shows that every vector can be decomposed into two parts: 1) its project=
ion on
   an orthonormal set and 2) a residual that is orthogonal to the given
   orthonormal set.
</p>
<div class=3D"proposition">
   <p><span class=3D"titoletto">Proposition</span>
      Let
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$S$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4161px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
      be a vector space equipped with an inner product
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"26" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq5]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3526px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>.
      Let
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"94" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq6]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2457px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>
      be an orthonormal set. For any
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"38" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$sin S$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3380px;v=
ertical-align:-5px"></span>,
      we
      have<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"151" height=
=3D"71" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq7]" style=3D"background-position:0px =
-1466px;"></span>where
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$varepsilon _{S}$" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -3816px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
      is orthogonal to
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{k}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3791px;v=
ertical-align:-5px"></span>
      for any
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"87" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$k=3D1,ldots ,K.$" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -2507px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
   </p>
</div>

<div class=3D"bproof"><span class=3D"bproof">Proof</span></div>
<div id=3D"idn1" class=3D"clps"><div class=3D"proofline">
<p>Define<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"151" height=
=3D"68" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq8]" style=3D"background-position:0px =
-1398px;"></span>Then,
   for each
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"78" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$j=3D1,ldots ,K$" style=3D"background-position:0px -262=
0px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>,
   we have
   that<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"227" height=3D"=
322" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAA=
AABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq9]" style=3D"background-position:0px -46=
2px;"></span>where:
   in steps
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"34" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$frame{A}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3971px;ve=
rtical-align:-8px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"34" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$frame{B}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3937px;ve=
rtical-align:-8px"></span>
   we have used the fact that the inner product is linear in its first argu=
ment;
   in step
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"34" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$frame{C}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3757px;ve=
rtical-align:-8px"></span>
   we have used the fact that
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"76" height=3D"26" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq10]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2671px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   if
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"37" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$k
eq j$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3405px;vertical-align:-5px"></span=
>
   since we are dealing with an orthonormal set; in step
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"34" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$frame{D}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3723px;ve=
rtical-align:-8px"></span>
   we have used the fact that the norm of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"16" height=3D"26" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{j}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4111px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   is equal to 1. Therefore,
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$varepsilon _{S}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -36=
99px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>,
   as defined above, is orthogonal to all the elements of the orthonormal s=
et,
   which proves the proposition.
</p>
</div></div>
<p>
   The
   term<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"95" height=3D"6=
8" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAA=
BAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq11]" style=3D"background-position:0px -234=
1px;"></span>is
   called the linear projection of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"9" height=3D"24" src=3D"d=
ata:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRA=
EAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$s$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4210px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   on the orthonormal set
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"65" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq12]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2978px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>,
   while the term
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$varepsilon _{S}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -38=
16px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
   is called the residual of the linear projection.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid4" class=3D"subsection">Normalization</h2>
<p>
   Another perhaps obvious fact that we are going to repeatedly use in the
   Gram-Schmidt process is that, if we take any non-zero vector and we divi=
de it
   by its norm, then the result of the division is a new vector that has un=
it
   norm.
</p>
<p>
   In other words, if
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"52" height=3D"38" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq13]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3173px;=
"></span>
   then, by the  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/vector-=
norm">definiteness property of
   the norm</a>, we have that
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"71" height=3D"38" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq14]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2891px;=
"></span>
</p>
<p>
   As a consequence, we can
   define<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"83" height=3D=
"50" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAA=
AABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq15]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2=
570px;"></span>and,
   by the positivity and absolute homogeneity of the norm, we
   have<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"150" height=3D"=
136" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAA=
AABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq16]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1=
575px;"></span>
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid5" class=3D"subsection">Overview of the procedure</h2>
<p>
   Now that we know how to normalize a vector and how to decompose it into =
a
   projection on an orthonormal set and a residual, we are ready to explain=
 the
   Gram-Schmidt procedure.
</p>
<p>
   We are going to provide an overview of the process, after which we will
   express it formally as a proposition and we will discuss all the technic=
al
   details in the proof of the proposition.
</p>
<p>
   Here is the overview.
</p>
<p>
   We are given a set of linearly independent vectors
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"61" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq17]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3125px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   To start the process, we normalize the first vector, that is, we
   define<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"107" height=
=3D"50" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq18]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -2027px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   In the second step, we project
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$s_{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3913px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   on
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"19" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{1}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3627px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=
=3D"146" height=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wA=
AACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq19]" style=3D"backgrou=
nd-position:0px -1711px;"></span>where
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$varepsilon _{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -36=
75px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
   is the residual of the projection.
</p>
<p>
   Then, we normalize the
   residual:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"109" heigh=
t=3D"50" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAAL=
AAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq20]" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -1977px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   We will later prove that
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"47" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq21]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3235px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   (so that the normalization can be performed) because the starting vector=
s are
   linearly independent.
</p>
<p>
   The two vectors
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"19" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{1}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3627px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"19" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3603px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   thus obtained are orthonormal.
</p>
<p>
   In the third step, we project
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$s_{3}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3889px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   on
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"19" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{1}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3627px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"19" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3603px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=
=3D"226" height=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wA=
AACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq22]" style=3D"backgrou=
nd-position:0px -784px;"></span>and
   we compute the residual of the projection
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$varepsilon _{3}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -36=
51px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   We then normalize
   it:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"109" height=3D"5=
0" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAA=
BAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq23]" style=3D"background-position:0px -192=
7px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   We proceed in this manner until we obtain the last normalized residual
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{K} $" style=3D"background-position:0px -3579px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   At the end of the process, the vectors
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"65" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq24]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2954px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   form an orthonormal set because:
</p>
<ol>
   <li>
      <p>
         they are the result of a normalization, and as a consequence they =
have unit
         norm;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         each
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"25" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{k}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3791px=
;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         is obtained from a residual that has the property of being orthogo=
nal to
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"75" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq25]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2721px;=
vertical-align:-5px"></span>.
      </p>
   </li>
</ol>
<p>
   To complete this overview, let us remember that the
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/linear-span">linear =
span</a> of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"61" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq17]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3125px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   is the set of all vectors that can be written as
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/linear-combinations"=
>linear combinations</a> of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"61" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq17]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3125px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>;
   it is denoted
   by<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"117" height=3D"38=
" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAAB=
AAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq28]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1889=
px;"></span>and
   it is a  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/linear-space=
s">linear space</a>.
</p>
<p>
   Since the vectors
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"65" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq29]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2954px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   are linearly independent combinations of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"61" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq17]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3125px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>,
   any vector that can be written as a linear combination of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"61" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq17]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3125px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   can also be written as a linear combination of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"65" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq29]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2954px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>.
   Therefore, the spans of the two sets of vectors
   coincide:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"242" heigh=
t=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAAL=
AAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq33]" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -145px;"></span>
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid6" class=3D"subsection">Formal statement</h2>
<p>
   We formalize here the Gram-Schmidt process as a proposition, whose proof
   contains all the technical details of the procedure.
</p>
<div class=3D"proposition">
   <p><span class=3D"titoletto">Proposition</span>
      Let
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$S$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4161px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
      be a vector space equipped with an inner product
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"26" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq5]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3526px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>.
      Let
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"90" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq35]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2482px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
      be linearly independent vectors. Then, there exists a set of orthonor=
mal
      vectors
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"65" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq36]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2929px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
      such
      that<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"238" height=
=3D"41" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq37]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -383px;"></span>for
      any
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"43" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$kleq K$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3307px;=
vertical-align:-5px"></span>.
   </p>
</div>

<div class=3D"bproof"><span class=3D"bproof">Proof</span></div>
<div id=3D"idn2" class=3D"clps"><div class=3D"proofline">
<p>The proof is by induction: first we prove
   that the proposition is true for
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"40" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$k=3D1$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3356px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>,
   and then we prove that it is true for a generic
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"k" style=3D"background-position:0px -4186px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   if it holds for
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"36" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$k-1$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3454px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>.
   When
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"40" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$k=3D1$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3332px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>,
   the
   vector<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"107" height=
=3D"50" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq18]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -2027px;"></span>has
   unit norm and it constitutes by itself an orthonormal set: there are no =
other
   vectors, so the orthogonality condition is trivially satisfied. The
   set<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"72" height=3D"38=
" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAAB=
AAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq39]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2829=
px;"></span>is
   the set of all scalar multiples of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$s_{1}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3865px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>,
   which are also scalar multiples of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"19" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$u_{1}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3627px;verti=
